☎️4087189371. “Dot Mandala Buddha”: I am so excited to share my new creation, been thinking about it since long and finally its here\uD83D\uDE00 plz provide ur feedback\uD83D\uDE4F I tried to blend both mandala and dot painting art forms in a therapeutic fashion. A mandala: which is “circle” in Sanskrit and is a spiritual and ritual symbol in some cultures representing the universe. The circular designs symbolizes the idea that life is never ending and everything is connected. So the first level is understanding the unity in cosmos and secondly each individual must find their own place within it. Dot painting originated from aboriginal Australia and a mandala in Sanskrit means a circle representing the universe. Mandalas have many uses apart from meditation as the the designs are meant to remove irritating thoughts and allow the creative mind to run free as well as relaxation. But ultimately people create and look at mandalas to centre the body and mind. Over 500 people watched SETU’s production of “Seven Steps Around the Fire” live and supported/donated for a great cause. The play is written by renowned playwright Mahesh Dattani and directed by Subrata Das, which raises awareness about the most oppressed society in India. The virtual play, with two shows with a double cast, received rave reviews and overwhelmingly positive feedback from the community members. It was simply marvelous and enthralled the audience in the virtual setting. Our sincere thanks to the sponsors, donors, and all the community members for supporting the joint effort and the great cause. Those who missed watching the play live, here is an opportunity to watch the recorded videos, and both plays are not to be missed. Please do watch at your convenience from the comforts of your home, and consider donating to support the local pantries and shelters. No amount is too small. These were special moments to see a family reunion of love, to enjoy a day for him to relive his best moments, and to showcase his artwork. Thank you, Loren, for an outstanding support and experience. May the Pahsetopah family be blessed with the presence of Loren while he was here with us. As you prepare for the Homecoming Celebration, AIHD wish you peace and A mandala: which is “circle” in Sanskrit and is a spiritual and ritual symbol in some cultures representing the universe. The circular designs symbolizes the idea that life is never ending and everything is connected. So the first level is understanding the unity in cosmos and secondly each individual must find their own place within it. Dot painting originated from aboriginal Australia and a mandala in Sanskrit means a circle representing the universe. Mandalas have many uses apart from meditation as the the designs are meant to remove irritating thoughts and allow the creative mind to run free as well as relaxation. But ultimately people create and look at mandalas to centre the body and mind. both mandala and dot painting art forms in a therapeutic fashion. A mandala: which is “circle” in Sanskrit and is a spiritual and ritual symbol in some cultures representing the universe. The circular designs symbolizes the idea that life is never ending and everything is connected. So the first level is understanding the unity in cosmos and secondly each individual must find their own place within it. Dot painting originated from aboriginal Australia and a mandala in Sanskrit means a circle representing the universe. Mandalas have many uses apart from meditation as the the designs are meant to remove irritating thoughts and allow the creative mind to run free as well as relaxation. But ultimately people create and look at mandalas to centre the body and mind. 01:17:20","updated":"2021-12-11 13:20:58","type":"photo","description":"IE Exclusive: Woman Gives Birth to Baby Boy Midair in India amid Pandemic  \n\nA baby was destined to be born midair this week, whereas people are rethinking their travel plans amid the pandemic. This miracle happened at 30,000 feet aboard a Bengaluru-bound flight from New Delhi operated by IndiGo Airlines on October 8. All of a sudden, a woman traveler experienced labor pain and gave birth to a baby boy prematurely onboard. Coincidentally, a gynecologist named Dr. Shailaja Vallabhani was traveling on the same flight. The woman was allowed to board the flight as her pregnancy was not over 32 weeks. On learning about the woman’s labor pain and her history of miscarriage, the gynecologist came forward and set up a makeshift labor room in the gallery of the flight with the help of the flight attendants. \n\nA few minutes later, the newborn’s cries filled the plane with joy. The passengers gave a thunderous applause to Dr. Shailaja Vallabhani and the IndiGo crew members. Though the baby was born premature, both the mother and the newborn were safe and in good health. The pilot of IndiGo’s 6E122 flight confirmed that the flight operations were normal during the midair delivery process amid all precautions. Following a great welcome at Bengaluru’s Kempegowda Airport, the mother and the newborn were taken to a nearby medical facility. Reportedly, the newborn may get a free lifetime subscription to IndiGo’s domestic flights.\n\nThe inflight birth of the baby boy is a silver lining to the dark clouds hovering over aviation. (Picture credit: IndiGo Airlines)","message":"A baby was destined to be born midair this week, whereas people are rethinking their travel plans amid the pandemic. This miracle happened at 30,000 feet aboard a Bengaluru-bound flight from New Delhi operated by IndiGo Airlines on October 8. All of a sudden, a woman traveler experienced labor pain and gave birth to a baby boy prematurely onboard. Coincidentally, a gynecologist named Dr. Shailaja Vallabhani was traveling on the same flight. The woman was allowed to board the flight as her pregnancy was not over 32 weeks. On learning about the woman’s labor pain and her history of miscarriage, the gynecologist came forward and set up a makeshift labor room in the gallery of the flight with the help of the flight attendants. A few minutes later, the newborn’s cries filled the plane with joy. The passengers gave a thunderous applause to Dr. Shailaja Vallabhani and the IndiGo crew members. Though the baby was born premature, both the mother and the newborn were safe and in good health. The pilot of IndiGo’s 6E122 flight confirmed that the flight operations were normal during the midair delivery process amid all precautions. Following a great welcome at Bengaluru’s Kempegowda Airport, the mother and the newborn were taken to a nearby medical facility. Reportedly, the newborn may get a free lifetime subscription to IndiGo’s domestic flights. The inflight birth of the baby boy is a silver lining to the dark clouds hovering over Holding you in awe, you stop in your tracks. These films compel you to reflect. You don't quite see that in typical mainstream cinema. Directors, many of them women, narrate their stories in a style that's most unusual. In fact, some stories have elements which we may have pushed to the far recesses of our own mind. Others are out of the ordinary stories about people you may have never heard of. Yet others are stories about those you are unlikely to meet in real life. But filmmakers have brought these stories to us. You'll find diversity of language, cultures, even another era, and yet the stories will strike a chord, regardless. They will touch you in a way you may have least expected. Here's a wonderful opportunity to watch 16 feature films + 3 feature length documentaries + 4 collections of short films. You could get a Pass to watch all these 50+ films, or take your pick. One movie a night is possible. You have 18 days from October 15th through November 1st including three weekends. Indeed, many virtual events are available gratis in present day. Here's a small price to pay for films that are enjoyable, evocative and engaging. At least for these few days I'm going to set aside all other entertainment in support of indie filmmakers. Indian Film Festival of Cincinnati has taken immense efforts to curate these films from almost 400 submissions. Filmmakers are eager and excited for an audience in North America. For this, all films are subtitled in English. Do check the Film Guide. If you like what you see there, book your tickets or Buy your Pass. During this time, Persian, Rajasthani and other Indian schools of art got united to invent a synthesis of aesthetics. The same trend was visible in other costumes also. The Persian and Indian designs on silk texture studded with gold and silver remained the sign of Mughal era. Though intricate pure gold and silver designs are not there today, still zari has taken its position as a signature material.\n\nThink of a festive celebration or traditional function and the Benarasi saree instantly comes into mind. Not only is it one of the most classical attire available to us, it reminds us of all the precious times we have spent with our near and dear ones at such gala occasions. A mandala: which is “circle” in Sanskrit and is a spiritual and ritual symbol in some cultures representing the universe. The circular designs symbolizes the idea that life is never ending and everything is connected. So the first level is understanding the unity in cosmos and secondly each individual must find their own place within it. Dot painting originated from aboriginal Australia and a mandala in Sanskrit means a circle representing the universe. Mandalas have many uses apart from meditation as the the designs are meant to remove irritating thoughts and allow the creative mind to run free as well as relaxation. But ultimately people create and look at mandalas to centre the body and mind. 01:00:26","updated":"2021-12-11 13:21:03","type":"photo","description":"IE exclusive: Chandamama Visual Artist Sivasankar Breathes His Last  \n\nComic books with visual illustrations used to be the most engaging companion of children and teenagers during train journeys until the smartphone boom in India. Those who grew up in the 70s, the 80s and the 90s might cherish the memories of fighting with their siblings over the first reading of the most popular magazine ‘Chandamama’ which was published in 13 regional languages. Karatholuvu Chandrasekaran Sivasankaran, who built his immortal identity as the sketch artist of the Vikram Vetal series in the magazine over six decades of his career, breathed his last at the age of 97 yesterday. Born in Tamil Nadu in 1927, he showed signs of a budding visual artist at a tender age. His talent for drawing and sketching was discovered by a school teacher in 1934. \n\nOn completion of his schooling, he enrolled in Chennai’s Government Arts College for a 5-year art course. Upon successful graduation, he started his career with a Tamil magazine named Kalai Magal. Since the day he was hired as an in-house artist for Chandamama, a periodical magazine for children, there was no looking back. It was him who gave visual life to the Vikram Vetal stories through creative illustration. He also sketched several other regional stories and folklores for children. He retired in 2012 when Chandamama magazine pulled down its shutter due to the increasing dominance of digital content.","message":"Comic books with visual illustrations used to be the most engaging companion of children and teenagers during train journeys until the smartphone boom in India. Those who grew up in the 70s, the 80s and the 90s might cherish the memories of fighting with their siblings over the first reading of the most popular magazine ‘Chandamama’ which was published in 13 regional languages. Karatholuvu Chandrasekaran Sivasankaran, who built his immortal identity as the sketch artist of the Vikram Vetal series in the magazine over six decades of his career, breathed his last at the age of 97 yesterday. Born in Tamil Nadu in 1927, he showed signs of a budding visual artist at a tender age. His talent for drawing and sketching was discovered by a school teacher in 1934. On completion of his schooling, he enrolled in Chennai’s Government Arts College for a 5-year art course. Upon successful graduation, he started his career with a Tamil magazine named Kalai Magal. Since the day he was hired as an in-house artist for Chandamama, a periodical magazine for children, there was no looking back. It was him who gave visual life to the Vikram Vetal stories through creative illustration. He also sketched several other regional stories and folklores for children. He retired in 2012 when Chandamama magazine pulled down its shutter due to the increasing dominance of digital
